snippet.textDisplay: Doug DeMuro Douglas, you couldn’t possibly be more wrong about the amount of times people use their washer fluid. Up in upstate New York where it snows in there is salt and mud for 7 straight months, and it’s just generally a miserable place to be and I constantly contemplate to myself why I’m even here still, I go through about a gallon of washer fluid every two weeks. And it does smell to a certain extent, but I’m one of those weirdos that happened to enjoy the smell of washer fluid wafting in from the outside. However, if somebody is so inclined they can simply hit the “close the recirculation” button then use their washer fluid stalk, finish with the washing, and then hit the “de-recirculate button” once more time. Such is life in the cold environment. Kurt Vonnegut would get a kick out of it.

snippet.textDisplay:
I don't know when Hyundai started selling cars in the US, but I can remember when they were first imported to Australia in 1988. They were butt-ugly, but with a Mitsubishi engine and a robust interior, they managed to survive the original scepticism. Then the Excel came out for around 13K (AUD) with power steering & aircon. All of a sudden they sold like hot-cakes and seemed to be everywhere on the road.


Fast forward to 2020 and a Hyundai is a car that can hold it's own against any Japanese brand. I never thought that they would make it this far.
snippet.textOriginal:

All of a sudden they sold like hot-cakes and seemed to be everywhere on the road.


Fast forward to 2020 and a Hyundai is a car that can hold it's own against any Japanese brand. I never thought that they would make it this far.
